    <fr:title text="Degree of polynomial">Degree of polynomial</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:authors></fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>A <fr:link type="local" href="def-0027.xml" addr="def-0027" title="Polynomial">polynomial</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline">p\in  \mathcal {P}(R)</fr:tex> is said to have degree <fr:tex display="inline">n</fr:tex> if
    there exists coefficients <fr:tex display="inline">a_0, a_1, \ldots , a_n \in  R</fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline">a_n \neq  0</fr:tex> such that
    <fr:tex display="block">         p(x) = a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 x^2 + \cdots  + a_n x^n     </fr:tex>
    for all <fr:tex display="inline">x \in  R</fr:tex>. We denote the degree of <fr:tex display="inline">p</fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline">\deg (p) = n</fr:tex>.
    For the zero polynomial, we define its degree to be <fr:tex display="inline">-\infty </fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
